<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-569-671  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 569 671.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  Oct 29 1990 v9 n23 p55(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Navy officials accept EDMICS as heart of CALS. (Engineering DataManagement Information Control System) (Computer-Aided Acquisitionand Logistics Support)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Green, Robert.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Advanced Technology Inc. (Contracts).andO;Topic:     United States. NavyImaging TechnologyGovernment Contracts.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Navy Officials Accept EDMICS as Heart of CALSandM;Navy officials have accepted the digital imaging system they believe will bethe cornerstone of their own Computer-Aided Acquisition and Logistics Support(CALS) program, and also the Defense Logistics Agency's program.andM;Naval Supply Systems Command officials last month completed six months ofacceptance testing at the naval ordinance station in Louisville, Ky., on theEngineering Data Management Information Control System.andM;Among other procedures, EDMICS was put through a 60-day continuous operationsequence in which system availability met the minimum 97 percent the Navycalled for when it contracted for the system from Advanced Technology Inc.andO;(ATI) of McLean, Va., in June 1989.andM;Next on the agenda for EDMICS, according to an ATI spokesman, is operationaltesting and evaluation, which is scheduled for completion by the end of theyear.andM;Future EDMICS users will examine the system during this phase of testing,said Michael Mooney, ATI's director of site liaison for the EDMICSinstallation.andM;EDMICS eventually will replace manual data repositories at 47 sites withinthe Navy, Marine Corps and DLA, officials have said.andM;Six Navy sites and two DLA sites are scheduled to receive EDMICS during 1991,Mooney said.andM;Newly received technical documentation for the CAD II design and engineeringsystems procurement and the Shipboard Non-Tactical ADP program already isbeing stored on EDMICS, and millions of older documents relating tomaintenance and operation of Navy systems and vessels will be scanned intothe system eventually.andM;ATI's principal subcontractor for the $154 million EDMICS project is XeroxCorp.andP;  About three-quarters of the EDMICS hardware and software is off theshelf.andM;Earlier this year, eight subsets of the Navy's CALS program were rolled intothe same budgeting stream that serves DOD's corporate information management(CIM) program, raising speculation that EDMICS might one day serve as a CALSplatform for the Army and Air Force as well.andM;In the spring of next year, officials have said, the air force will transfera large volume of engineering data to DLA sites running EDMICS.andP;  Speculationhas been that several Air Force sites might be asked to take on EDMICS aspart of that data transfer, one official said.andO;</TEXT></DOC>